          "name": "How to calculate EBITDA margin?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "EBITDA margin is EBITDA divided by revenue, expressed as a percentage. A company with revenue of Rs 10 crore and EBITDA of Rs 1.8 crore has an EBITDA margin of 18 percent. Use revenue from operations, not other income, in the denominator, otherwise the margin is overstated and will not match what a lender or investor computes."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are EBITDA and operating profit the same?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. Operating profit, or EBIT, is struck after depreciation and amortisation, while EBITDA adds those two back. If EBIT is Rs 70 lakh and depreciation is Rs 20 lakh, EBITDA is Rs 90 lakh. The gap widens for asset heavy businesses, which is why a manufacturer can show healthy EBITDA and still report an operating loss."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does Schedule III require EBITDA to be shown in Indian financial statements?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Schedule III to the Companies Act 2013 has no EBITDA line, so EBITDA is a non-statutory measure computed outside the audited statements. It is built from the statement of profit and loss by adding back finance cost and depreciation to profit before tax. Because there is no prescribed definition, lenders and investors adjust it differently, so the basis should always be stated."
          }
        }
