<div class="gl-page">
  <section class="gl-hero"><div class="gl-wrap"><nav class="gl-crumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary">Glossary</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><span class="cur">EBITDA</span></nav><div class="gl-cat">Accounting Glossary &middot; Fundamentals</div><h1 class="gl-h1">What Is EBITDA? Meaning, Formula and Example</h1><div class="gl-byline"><span class="ok"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg></span><span class="who">Reviewed by CA &amp; CS Team, Patron Accounting LLP</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>Last updated 22 Jul 2026</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>5 min read</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span class="lvl">Beginner</span></div></div></section>
  <div class="gl-tocbar"><div class="gl-wrap gl-toc"><a href="#definition" class="gl-pill is-active">Definition</a><a href="#what-is" class="gl-pill">What it is</a><a href="#how-works" class="gl-pill">How it works</a><a href="#formula" class="gl-pill">Formula</a><a href="#example" class="gl-pill">Example</a><a href="#mistakes" class="gl-pill">Mistakes</a><a href="#faq-section" class="gl-pill">FAQs</a></div></div>
  <div class="gl-body"><div class="gl-wrap"><div class="gl-grid"><div class="gl-main"><section id="definition" class="gl-sec"><div class="gl-eyebrow">EBITDA: Definition</div><div class="definition-box"><p>EBITDA is earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortisation — a measure of a business&#x27;s operating profitability stripped of financing, tax and non-cash write-downs. It is not a line in statutory accounts but is derived from them. It matters because it approximates the cash a firm&#x27;s core operations generate, letting lenders and investors compare businesses without the noise of how each is financed or taxed.</p></div></section><section id="what-is" class="gl-sec"><h2>What Is EBITDA?</h2><p>EBITDA takes operating profit and adds back depreciation and amortisation, so it shows earnings before four things a business cannot fully control period to period: interest on its borrowings, tax, and the non-cash charges for writing down assets. What is left is a proxy for the cash-generating power of the core business, which is why it features heavily in loan covenants and valuation multiples.</p><p>A Chennai manufacturing company meets EBITDA whenever it raises funding or is valued for sale. A buyer often prices a business at a multiple of EBITDA, and a lender may cap borrowing at a multiple of it, because it compares operating performance across firms with different debt loads and asset bases. But it is a non-GAAP measure — not defined in the Companies Act or the accounting standards — so it must be read with care and reconciled back to profit, since it flatters a capital-heavy business by ignoring real depreciation.</p><div class="key-terms"><p class="key-terms__title">Key terms</p><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/assets">Assets</a> — The asset base whose depreciation EBITDA adds back.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/liabilities">Liabilities</a> — Borrowings whose interest EBITDA excludes.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/equity">Equity</a> — The owners&#x27; stake, valued often as a multiple of EBITDA.</li></ul></div></section><section id="characteristics" class="gl-sec"><h2>What EBITDA Includes and Excludes</h2><p>EBITDA deliberately counts operating performance and strips out financing, tax and non-cash items, which is what makes it comparable across firms:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Includes operating revenue and costs</strong> — Core sales less operating expenses such as materials, wages and overheads.</li><li><strong>Excludes interest</strong> — Finance costs are added back, so capital structure does not distort the comparison.</li><li><strong>Excludes tax</strong> — Tax is added back, removing the effect of differing tax positions.</li><li><strong>Excludes depreciation and amortisation</strong> — These non-cash write-downs are added back to approximate operating cash.</li><li><strong>Why it can mislead</strong> — By ignoring depreciation, it flatters asset-heavy firms and overlooks the real cost of replacing plant — read it with net profit and cash flow.</li></ul></section><section id="how-works" class="gl-sec"><h2>How EBITDA Is Used in Financial Analysis</h2><p>Lenders and investors use EBITDA in a defined sequence:</p><ol class="step-cards"><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">1</span><strong>Start from operating profit</strong><p>Take profit before interest and tax from the P&amp;L working.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">2</span><strong>Add back depreciation and amortisation</strong><p>These non-cash charges are added to reach the figure, a cash-flow proxy.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">3</span><strong>Compute the margin</strong><p>The result divided by revenue gives the margin, comparing operating efficiency across firms.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">4</span><strong>Test leverage</strong><p>Lenders check net debt to EBITDA to see how many years of operating earnings the debt represents.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">5</span><strong>Apply a valuation multiple</strong><p>Investors value the business at a multiple of EBITDA, adjusting for its capital needs and one-offs.</p></li></ol></section><section id="formula" class="gl-sec"><h2>How to Calculate EBITDA</h2><div class="formula-box"><code>EBITDA = Operating profit + Depreciation + Amortisation  (or: Net profit + Interest + Tax + Depreciation + Amortisation)</code></div><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Input</th><th>Where it comes from</th><th>Sample value (INR)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Operating profit (EBIT)</td><td>P&amp;L, before interest and tax</td><td>15,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Depreciation</td><td>P&amp;L depreciation and amortisation line</td><td>6,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Amortisation of intangibles</td><td>Notes to the accounts</td><td>1,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>EBITDA</td><td>Operating profit plus add-backs</td><td>22,00,000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="worked-result">EBITDA = 15,00,000 + 6,00,000 + 1,00,000 = ₹22,00,000; on revenue of ₹1,00,00,000 that is a 22% EBITDA margin.</p></section><section id="example" class="gl-sec"><h2>EBITDA: A Practical Example</h2><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Amount (INR)</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Revenue from operations</td><td>1,00,00,000</td><td>Top line</td></tr><tr><td>Operating expenses (excl. depreciation)</td><td>78,00,000</td><td>Materials, wages, overheads</td></tr><tr><td>EBITDA</td><td>22,00,000</td><td>Revenue less cash operating costs</td></tr><tr><td>Less: depreciation and amortisation</td><td>7,00,000</td><td>Non-cash charges</td></tr><tr><td>Operating profit (EBIT)</td><td>15,00,000</td><td>After depreciation</td></tr><tr><td>Less: interest and tax</td><td>6,25,000</td><td>Finance cost and tax</td></tr><tr><td>Net profit</td><td>8,75,000</td><td>Bottom line</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A Chennai manufacturer earns ₹1,00,00,000 of revenue with ₹78,00,000 of cash operating costs, giving EBITDA of ₹22,00,000 — a 22% margin. Deducting ₹7,00,000 of depreciation, then ₹6,25,000 of interest and tax, leaves net profit of ₹8,75,000. A buyer valuing the firm at, say, six times EBITDA would price it around ₹1.32 crore, but a careful buyer also checks the depreciation the EBITDA figure conveniently ignores.</p></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--error"><span class="gl-callout__ic">!</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Common error</div><p>Reading it as cash: Treating EBITDA as free cash flow ignores working capital and capex → read it with the cash flow statement.</p></div></div><section id="india" class="gl-sec"><h2>EBITDA Under Indian Accounting Rules</h2><p>EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure: it is not defined in the Companies Act 2013 and is not a line item in the Schedule III statement of profit and loss, which presents expenses by nature. It is therefore derived from the audited figures rather than reported within them. Listed companies that quote EBITDA in earnings releases must, under SEBI norms, reconcile such non-GAAP measures back to the nearest GAAP figure — typically profit before tax — so readers are not misled.</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Not defined in the Companies Act</strong> — EBITDA has no statutory definition and is not a Schedule III line.</li><li><strong>Derived, not reported</strong> — It is computed from audited revenue, expenses and depreciation.</li><li><strong>SEBI reconciliation</strong> — Listed companies must reconcile quoted EBITDA to a GAAP measure such as PBT.</li></ul></section><section id="mistakes" class="gl-sec"><h2>Common Mistakes With EBITDA</h2><p>The measure misleads when it is treated as more than a proxy:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Reading it as cash</strong> — Treating EBITDA as free cash flow ignores working capital and capex → read it with the cash flow statement.</li><li><strong>Ignoring depreciation entirely</strong> — Forgetting that assets must be replaced flatters asset-heavy firms → weigh depreciation as a real economic cost.</li><li><strong>Adding back too much</strong> — Labelling ordinary costs as one-offs to inflate &#x27;adjusted EBITDA&#x27; distorts the measure → add back only genuine non-recurring items.</li><li><strong>Comparing without reconciliation</strong> — Using an unreconciled EBITDA hides how it was built → reconcile it to profit before tax.</li></ul></section><section id="related" class="gl-sec"><h2>Related Accounting Terms</h2><p>Balance-sheet terms read alongside EBITDA:</p><ul class="related-terms"><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/assets">Assets</a> — The asset base whose depreciation is added back here.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/liabilities">Liabilities</a> — Borrowings whose interest the measure excludes.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/equity">Equity</a> — Valued often as a multiple of operating earnings.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary</a> — Browse every accounting term in one place.</li></ul></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--summary"><span class="gl-callout__ic">&#10003;</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Quick summary</div><p>EBITDA is earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortisation — a measure of a business&amp;#x27;s operating profitability stripped of financing, tax and non-cash write-downs. It is not a line in statutory accounts but is derived from them. It matters because it approximates the cash a firm&amp;#x27;s core operations generate, letting lenders and investors compare businesses without the noise of how each is financed or taxed.</p></div></div><section class="gl-cta"><div class="gl-cta__t"><h3>Need help with EBITDA?</h3><p>EBITDA sits inside your day-to-day books. Patron's CA-led team keeps them accurate, compliant and audit-ready.</p></div><div class="gl-cta__btns"><a class="gl-cta__primary" href="/mis-reporting-services">MIS Reporting Services &rarr;</a><a class="gl-cta__phone" href="tel:+919459456700">Book a consultation: +91 94594 56700</a></div></section></div><aside class="gl-aside"><div class="gl-card gl-card--service"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related service</div><div class="gl-card__name">MIS Reporting Services</div><p>CA-led bookkeeping, compliance and reporting for Indian businesses.</p><a class="gl-card__cta" href="/mis-reporting-services">Explore the service &rarr;</a></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related services</div><ul><li><a href="/financial-statement-preparation-services">Financial Statement Preparation<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related terms</div><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/assets">Assets<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/liabilities">Liabilities<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/equity">Equity<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div></aside></div></div></div>
  <section id="faq-section" class="gl-faq-section"><div class="faq-expanded"><aside class="faq-expanded__aside"><h2 class="faq-expanded__title">EBITDA FAQs</h2><p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about EBITDA for Indian businesses.</p><a class="faq-expanded__cta" href="/contact-us">Still have a question? Talk to a CA &rarr;</a><form class="faq-enquiry" action="https://www.patronaccounting.com/enquiry" method="post" novalidate><h3 class="faq-enquiry__title">Talk to a CA about your books</h3><p class="faq-enquiry__sub">Share your accounting software and we'll scope the work.</p><p class="faq-enquiry__context">Enquiring about: <strong>EBITDA</strong></p><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="text" name="name" placeholder="Your name" required><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><div class="faq-enquiry__phone"><span class="faq-enquiry__cc">+91</span><input class="faq-enquiry__input faq-enquiry__input--phone" type="tel" name="phone" placeholder="Mobile" required></div><button class="faq-enquiry__btn" type="submit">Get a Callback</button><p class="faq-enquiry__msg" role="status" aria-live="polite"></p><div class="faq-enquiry__badges"><span class="faq-enquiry__badge"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>CA-led team</span></div></form></aside><div class="faq-expanded__list"><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a1">How to calculate EBITDA margin?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a1"><p>EBITDA margin is EBITDA divided by revenue, expressed as a percentage. A company with revenue of Rs 10 crore and EBITDA of Rs 1.8 crore has an EBITDA margin of 18 percent. Use revenue from operations, not other income, in the denominator, otherwise the margin is overstated and will not match what a lender or investor computes.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a2">Are EBITDA and operating profit the same?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a2"><p>No. Operating profit, or EBIT, is struck after depreciation and amortisation, while EBITDA adds those two back. If EBIT is Rs 70 lakh and depreciation is Rs 20 lakh, EBITDA is Rs 90 lakh. The gap widens for asset heavy businesses, which is why a manufacturer can show healthy EBITDA and still report an operating loss.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a3">Does Schedule III require EBITDA to be shown in Indian financial statements?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a3"><p>Schedule III to the Companies Act 2013 has no EBITDA line, so EBITDA is a non-statutory measure computed outside the audited statements. It is built from the statement of profit and loss by adding back finance cost and depreciation to profit before tax. Because there is no prescribed definition, lenders and investors adjust it differently, so the basis should always be stated.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
